From: lxh <lmhtq1991@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 28 May 2026 12:30:00 +0800
Subject: [PATCH] Phase C-6 fix #6: cap-preserving mov(Register, Register) on CHERI

`MacroAssembler::mov(Register Rd, Register Rn)` on AArch64 encodes
as `orr Rd, ZR, Rn`. On CHERI Morello, ORR is an INTEGER op — it
copies the lower 64 bits but CLEARS THE TAG of any capability in
Rn during the move. Subsequent uses of Rd as a capability (load,
store, branch) fault with PROT_CHERI_TAG.

Concrete trigger: `StubRoutines::forward_exception` does
  __ mov(r19, r0);   // exception handler cap → r19
  __ br(r19);         // jump to handler
The first mov clears r19's tag; the br lands at the tag-zero PC and
the CPU faults at end-of-stub (the immediate-next instruction
address inside the stub blob).

Diagnosis path: cap_runtime SIGPROT handler (installed via patch
0087) captured si_addr=pc=0x428b8138, identified via -XX:+PrintStubCode
as the END of `StubRoutines::forward exception
[0x428b8100, 0x428b8138]`. Source inspection of generate_forward_exception
revealed the int-mov of a cap handler address.

Fix: under __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__, change mov(Rd, Rn) to use
`add Rd, Rn, #0` instead of `orr Rd, ZR, Rn`. On Morello, `add cap+0`
is the canonical cap-preserving move idiom — it preserves tag and
provenance. On classic AArch64 this is functionally equivalent (add
of integer + 0). The existing sp-case already used `add Rd, Rn, #0`
because ORR doesn't accept SP; we extend that path to all reg-reg
moves under CHERI.

Effect: with this patch, JVM init progresses past the forward_exception
SIGPROT and into TemplateInterpreterGenerator::generate_native_entry,
which exposes the NEXT layer (val=32 in 5-bit field at bits [9:5] —
register-number encoding overflow, likely a CHERI cap-register beyond
the AArch64 GP-register range). Documented in docs/26 (next session).

Scope note: this is a global change to all reg-reg moves, not just
forward_exception. Lots of other JVM paths benefit (any cap moved
between registers via the inline `mov` helper). The performance
difference between `orr Rd, ZR, Rn` and `add Rd, Rn, #0` is
negligible.

diff --git a/src/hotspot/cpu/aarch64/macroAssembler_aarch64.hpp b/src/hotspot/cpu/aarch64/macroAssembler_aarch64.hpp
--- a/src/hotspot/cpu/aarch64/macroAssembler_aarch64.hpp
+++ b/src/hotspot/cpu/aarch64/macroAssembler_aarch64.hpp
@@ -236,11 +236,23 @@
   inline void mov(Register Rd, Register Rn) {
     assert(Rd != r31_sp && Rn != r31_sp, "should be");
     if (Rd == Rn) {
     } else if (Rd == sp || Rn == sp) {
       Assembler::add(Rd, Rn, 0U);
     } else {
+#ifdef __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__
+      // C-6 fix #6: on CHERI purecap, register-to-register moves must
+      // be cap-preserving. The classic `orr Rd, ZR, Rn` is an INTEGER op
+      // that clears the cap tag of Rn during the copy. The Morello
+      // `add Rd, Rn, #0` preserves tag and provenance (it's the cap-mov
+      // idiom). Concrete symptom: `__ mov(r19, r0)` in
+      // generate_forward_exception lost the tag of the exception
+      // handler address, so the subsequent `br r19` SIGPROT'd at the
+      // tag-zero PC.
+      Assembler::add(Rd, Rn, 0U);
+#else
       orr(Rd, zr, Rn);
+#endif
     }
   }
